{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":758,"record_hash":"sha256:93cb65e74e0ccfb8cf22dfa45cb8b7b44f68eb686c0fb770d082e1483bc1c5cc","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:03:43.853Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 9035ed\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1079\nOutput:\n- broad or truncated file lists weaken file-overlap evidence\n- multiple visible branches/stacks weaken branch-name evidence\n- missing or failed environment snapshots simply produce less evidence\n\n## Session-Level Versus Turn-Level Association\n\nAssociation data from turns should produce derived session-level results on\nread. A branch, review, change, or PR view can show the whole related session\nwhile highlighting the turns that carried the evidence.\n\nThe cautious default is derived propagation. It avoids making the session claim\ntoo much, while still allowing branch/PR views to show relevant sessions.\n\nPersisted propagation may still be useful after explicit confirmation, but it\nshould probably mean \"this session is relevant to this target\", not \"this\nsession generated this target.\"\n\nGitButler's multiple-branches-in-one-worktree model is the main argument for\nturn-scoped precision. A single agent session can mostly build one feature\nbranch while a specific turn produces a bugfix that the user sends to another\nbranch. Whole-session association is therefore useful but not always precise\nenough for review sharing.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n- store sessions as the durable transcript object\n- start with durable relationships from a target to a session key\n- let turn evidence highlight or filter the relevant part of the session\n- allow future relationship metadata to carry optional turn scope when evidence\n  or user confirmation justifies it\n\nIn other words, turn scope should refine a session relationship. It should not\nmove transcript ownership onto branches, changes, commits, or pull requests.\n\n## Persist Or Recompute\n\nThe turn layer could be stored directly, or some of it could be recomputed from\nexisting records and Git state.\n\nReasons to persist turns:\n\n- preserves exact capture boundaries\n- preserves repository state at the time of capture\n- supports later association even after branches or worktree state ch\n[TRUNCATED]\nnvironment snapshots. Use them to compute association suggestions. Persist\nrelationships only when explicit user/API intent or a later product decision\njustifies it.\n- Turn write atomicity: GitMeta supports mixed atomic edits via\n  `MetaEdit::SetValue`; bump the pinned `git-meta-lib` dependency before\n  implementing turn writes.\n- Provider grouping: transcript records should gain an optional normalized\n  provider turn key for UI grouping, hashed/redacted when present.\n- Previous turn links: store `previous_turn_key` when a previous capture turn in\n  the same session is known.\n- Environment publication boundary: repo-scoped GitMeta exchange can include\n  branch names, relative file paths, PR identifiers, change ids, commit ids, and\n  commit file lists; what extra controls are needed before exposing a selected\n  web view outside normal repository access?\n- Snapshot size cap: path lists use a cap of 256 entries, plus `file_count` and\n  `files_truncated`.\n- Index rebuild/versioning: branch, review, and change indexes are the likely\n  first set; where should rebuild behavior live, and how should stale derived\n  lookup entries be invalidated?\n- Stack model: use a shared GitButler workspace/head-info API that supports both\n  GitButler and plain Git modes; do not add an agentlog-specific plain-Git model\n  unless the shared API proves insufficient.\n- Checked-out references and graph entrypoint markers are not stored in the turn\n  snapshot.\n- Association strength: first scoring version should be automatic, read-time,\n  explainable, and conservative; tune exact thresholds after implementation.\n- Confirmation UX: no required human confirmation for v1. UI may show derived\n  high-confidence related sessions automatically, with reasons.\n- Relationship scope: what is the smallest metadata shape that supports a\n  target-to-session relationship plus optional turn scope?\n- Propagation: if turn evidence points at a change id, should branch and PR\n  views derive that relationship, or should confirmed metadata be copied upward?\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:03:43.853Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}